\section*{\centering \textit {18.11.1 Properties of confluent hypergeometric functions}}
\noindent The properties of confluent hypergeometric functions can be derived from those of ordinary hypergeometri functions by letting \textit{$x\rightarrow $} \textit{$x/b$} and taking the limit \textit{$b\rightarrow$} \textit{$\infty$}, in the same way as both the equation and its solution wew derived.A general procedure of this sort is called \textit{$confluence$} process.

\smallskip
$$ \textit{Special cases}$$
\smallskip
\noindent The general nature of the confluent hypergeometric equation allows one to write a large number of elementary functions in terms of the confluent hypergeometric functions \textit{ M(A,C;X)}. Once again, such identifications can be made from the series expansions (18.148) directly, or by transformations of the confluent hypergeometric quation into a more familiar equation for which the solutions are already known.Some particular examples of well known secial cases of the confluent hypergeometric function ar as follows:\bigskip
\justifying
\begin{align*}
    \begin{split}
    M(a,a;x)=e^x,
    \end{split}
    \begin{split}
       M(1,2;2X)=\frac{e^x sinh x }{x}, 
    \end{split}\\
    \begin{split}
        M(-n,1;x)=L_n(x),
    \end{split}
            \begin{split}
    M(-n,m+1;x)=\frac{n!m!}{(n+m)!}L_n^m(x),
    \end{split}\\
    \begin{split}
        M(-n, \frac{1}{2};x^2)=\frac{(-1)^nn!}{(2n)!}H_{2n}(x)
    \end{split}
    \begin{split}
        M(-n, \frac{3}{2};x^2),=\frac{(-1)^nn!}{2(2n+1)!}\frac{H_{2n+1}(x)}{x},
    \end{split}\\
    \begin{split}
        M(v+ \frac{1}{2},2v+1;2ix)=v!e^{ix}(\frac{x}{2})^{-v}
J_v(x),    
\end{split}
\begin{split}
    M(\frac{1}{2}, \frac{3}{2};-x^2)=\frac{\sqrt{\pi}}{2x}erf(x)
\end{split}
\end{align*}
\noindent where $n$ and $m$ are integers $L_n^m$ is an associatef Legendre polynomial, $H_n(x)$ is a Hermite polynomial, $J_v(x)$ is a Bessel function and erf(x) is the error function discussed in section 18.12.4
\medskip
$$ \textit{Integral representation}$$
\noindent Using te integral reprsentation (18.144) of the ordinary hypergeometric function, exchangin $a$ and $b$ and carring out the process of confluece gives
\begin{align*}
    \begin{split}
    M(a,c,x)=\frac{\Gamma (c)}{\Gamma (a)\gamma(c-a)}\int^1_0 e^{tx}t{a-1}(1-t)^{c-a-1}dt,
    \end{split}
    \end{align*} 
